      <abstract>
      <variablelist>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>WHAT?</term>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              Multipath I/O provides redundant physical paths between a server and storage to enable automatic failover and traffic load balancing.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>WHY?</term>
          <listitem>
            <para>
              Learn about Multipath I/O because it prevents catastrophic system downtime by ensuring your servers never lose access to their data if a storage cable, switch, or adapter fails.
            </para>
          </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>EFFORT</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                The average reading time of this article is approximately an hour.
              </para>
            </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>GOAL</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
               To understand how to build resilient, high-performance IT infrastructure that keeps critical systems running during hardware failures.
              </para>
            </listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
          <term>REQUIREMENTS</term>
            <listitem>
              <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    <emphasis>Linux fundamentals:</emphasis> Understanding basic Linux commands, file permissions, directory structures
                    and use of the command line.
                  </para>
                </listitem>
<listitem><para><emphasis>Networking and storage basics:</emphasis> To manage Linux storage fabrics, you must understand that enterprise storage addresses devices using either 64-bit hardware World Wide Names (WWNs) for Fibre Channel networks or text-based IQNs (iSCSI Qualified Names) for standard Ethernet networks.</para></listitem>
              </itemizedlist>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
